disease_via_the_good_guys.description:
Disease (pathology) is equal to the number of pathogens encountered accounting for their Virulence (how well they can evade the immune system) divided by host resistance.&#13;
&#13;
Most disease comes from the normally avirulent commensal microbes (bacteria, fungi, viruses) becoming opportunistic pathogens via a sharp increase in their N (number) in inapropriate locations. This overwhelms the immune system as it is unable to respond to such a sudden sharp increase in the number of microbes it must deal with. This can happen from open wounds or tissues that are exposed. Our goal when thinking of care that involves exposure to pathogens should consider this relationship. &#13;
&#13;
How can we implement solutions that communicate how to decrease N in the pregnancy and birthing processes?

