indian_farmers_empowered_thanks_to_mkris.description:
Farmers and mothers have different issues, but in this case, TCS's mKrishi is a great inspiration as the two projects are facing similar issues:&#13;
- Language -- TCS had to find a technology that could be used by people in their own local language. The language issue is one of the most important barrier to big-scale project in low-income country&#13;
- Connection Experts/Farmers. As Dr Arun Pande, head of TCS Innovation Labs – Mumbai expalins, the biggest challenge “was to develop a scalable system which would also simulate the visits of experts to the farms. This was achieved by enabling the farms to travel to the expert instead of having the experts travel to the farms.”&#13;

free_access_to_information_for_informed_.description:
Historically development aid from NGO’s and from Government will normally focus on one or more specific areas of need within the community. In a few contexts, such as the Millennium Village programme, a concerted effort has been made to address all of the issues together in the community, with the concept that this broad approach will move the community out of extreme poverty. &#13;
Underlying all issues is a lack of resources within the community and a lack of capital assets to be able to draw on in times of need. The lack of financial capital is well known and is being addressed through the work of microfinance organisations and other initiatives. What is often not so easily understood is the lack of knowledge resources that exist within the communities.&#13;
It is the last of these areas, the lack of knowledge capital that we are looking to address with the concept of BluPoint. It is knowledge released to the community that will underpin and empower other initiatives to improve maternal health and wellbeing.&#13;

